INSERT INTO `webform_submitted_data` (`nid`,`sid`,`cid`,`no`,`data`) VALUES (10,26,48,'0','The data was processed using Excel and SPSS.  \r\nFor the data aggregated to the parcel level, SPSS was used to join the water consumption data set with Salt Lake County Tax Assessor variables about the structure where a given water meter is located.  To do this, the water consumption records were aggregated to the parcel level and then joined on the basis of the parcel ID. \r\n\r\nFor the data aggregated to the household level, there is water consumption data only (no tax assessor variables).  The process was more complicated than the parcel aggregation, due to the existence of duplicate records.  A step by step outline of the household data aggregation process follows (it may be best to copy and paste the outline into a word document):\r\n\r\n\r\n1.	Flattened records with both a lawn and culinary meters at a single address within each year.\r\na.	Without flattening these records, the separate meters would yield only half of the water consumed in the structure in question.  \r\nb.	Process: \r\ni.	Identify records with lawn meter that have same owner AND address as another record that is not designated as a lawn meter. \r\nii.	Flagged these records with a binary field: “Needs Aggregation.”\r\niii.	Sorted data by “Needs Aggregation” variable. Each record had at least one other record with a duplicate combination of (owner name x service address). \r\niv.	Created pivot tables to aggregate the records on the basis of the unique ID (owner name x service address).\r\n1.	Had to create two pivot tables and sort them both on the basis of the unique ID and then combine the tables in order to get all of the variables (the pivot tables limit the number of columns to 13).\r\nv.	Joined the aggregated records to the rest of the records within each year (this was a separate process that I repeated for both 2011 and 2012).\r\n\r\n2.	Deleted all records that were not residential housing (single-family housing, duplexes, triplexes, fourplexes, apartments). \r\na.	Deleted service types include:\r\ni.	Business\r\nii.	Industry\r\niii.	Parks and Municipal\r\niv.	Schools, Churches, Charities\r\nv.	Hospitals\r\nvi.	Restaurants\r\nvii.	Miscellaneous\r\n\r\n3.	Identified and deleted duplicate records, \r\na.	Duplicate record = records where there were two records with the same unique ID (owner name x service address).  \r\nb.	Process:\r\ni.	Flagged duplicates with binary field: “IsDupe” =1\r\nii.	sorted on: IsDupe, UID, Service ID\r\nc.	2011: \r\ni.	Identified 572 records with a duplicate UID.\r\nii.	~120 had NO consumption for the whole year\r\niii.	Some showed consumption first part of year, dupe showed consumption remainder of the year\r\niv.	Spot-checking indicated that some were units under construction\r\nv.	Lack of clear consistent pattern\r\nvi.	Deleted these records ( <.0% of all records).\r\nd.	2012:\r\ni.	 Identified 524 records with duplicate UID.\r\nii.	107 had no consumption for the whole year\r\niii.	Deleted these records ( <.0% of all records) --- (524/79,606)\r\n4.	Prepared data for join\r\na.	Determined that to use the quasi-experimental model, need to join years based on service ID.  To do this, it was necessary to remove duplicate service ID’s within years.\r\nb.	Process:\r\ni.	Flagged records with data for each month in growth season (April-September)\r\n1.	2011: 79,077-66,926 = 12,150 records dropped\r\n2.	2012: 79,081-67,056 = 12,025 records dropped\r\nii.	Dropped within-year duplicates\r\n1.	2011: \r\na.	Dropped 333 duplicates (kept those with smallest account number if had exact same consumption- should be random)\r\nb.	N=66,594\r\n2.	2012:\r\na.	Dropped 221 duplicates (used same rule)\r\nb.	N=66,831\r\niii.	Created variable for Growth Season Water Consumption in both 2011 & 2012.\r\n5.	Merged the two years\r\na.	Delete 3,800 records with data in 2012 but not 2011\r\nb.	Delete 3,200 records with data in 2011 but not 2012 (doesn’t exist at all)\r\ni.	Note: The reason that there are so many service ID’s that don’t match between the two years is that I deleted records that didn’t have full growth season data in both years.  A given location may not have had data in each growth season month in one year, but did have complete data in the other.  \r\n6.	Generated new variables\r\na.	Created binary field for same account ID vs. Different\r\nb.	Created field for change in 2012-2011 growth season consumption\r\n');
